# a function to update LSOA LAD codes and names based on LSOA names so that Deprv matches Wards and Maps

def LADfix(search,LADname,LADcode):
    #update the Popn/Deprv datasets with LADs to match Ward/map files
    Popn.loc[Popn["LSOAname"].str.contains(pat=search),'LADname']  = LADname
    Popn.loc[Popn["LSOAname"].str.contains(pat=search),'LADcode']  = LADcode
    Deprv.loc[Deprv["LSOAname"].str.contains(pat=search),'LADname']  = LADname
    Deprv.loc[Deprv["LSOAname"].str.contains(pat=search),'LADcode']  = LADcode

#set LAD code/name to correct values
LADfix("Taunton Deane","Taunton Deane","E07000190")
LADfix("West Somerset","West Somerset","E07000191")
LADfix("Poole","Poole","E06000029")
LADfix("Bournemouth","Bournemouth","E06000028")
LADfix("Christchurch","Christchurch","E07000048")
LADfix("North Dorset","North Dorset","E07000050")
LADfix("West Dorset","West Dorset","E07000052")
LADfix("East Dorset","East Dorset","E07000049")
LADfix("Purbeck","Purbeck","E07000051")
LADfix("Weymouth and Portland","Weymouth and Portland","E07000053")
                    
Popn[Popn["LSOAname"].str.contains(pat="Purbeck")].groupby(["LADcode","LADname"]).count()

1.3.6. group the main dataset to give results by LA district: use MEAN() for the ranks, deciles and population %s and use SUM() for Population totals.

Analysis of Population data below shows that values for an LSOA range from 523 to 9551 - Population should therefore be used in weighting the Deprivation averages.

In [13]:
#  calculate weighted means for LAD

# calculate the total pop for an LAD
PopnLAD=PopDepLSOA[['LADcode','LADname','RegionName','TotalPop']].groupby(['LADcode','LADname','RegionName']).sum();
PopnLAD=PopnLAD.rename(columns = {'TotalPop':'LADPop'})

# create a copy of LSOA data and update the rank/deciles to weighted values before grouping by LAD
keycols=['LSOAcode', 'LSOAname', 'LADcode', 'LADname','RegionName']
rankcols = ['IMDRank', 'IMDDec',
       'IncRank', 'IncDec', 'EmpRank', 'EmpDec', 'EduRank', 'EduDec',
       'HealthRank', 'HealthDec', 'CrimeRank', 'CrimeDec', 'HouseRank',
       'HouseDec', 'EnvRank', 'EnvDec']
Popcols=['TotalPop', 'DepChildnPop', '16_59Pop',
       'OlderPop', 'WorkingPop', 'DepChildnPerc', 'OlderPerc', '16_59Perc',
       'WorkingPerc']
temp=pd.merge(PopDepLSOA,PopnLAD,how='inner',on=['LADcode','LADname','RegionName'])
temprank=temp[rankcols].apply(lambda x: x*temp['TotalPop']/temp['LADPop'], axis=0)
#
tempkey=temp[keycols]
tempPop=temp[Popcols]
temp=pd.concat([tempkey,temprank,tempPop],axis=1)
PopDepLAD=temp.groupby(['LADcode','LADname','RegionName']).sum() # new weighted PopDepLAD
PopDepLAD = PopDepLAD.reset_index(drop=False)
PopDepLAD.sort_values(by=['IMDDec','RegionName','LADname']).head(10)

PopDepLAD['CrimeRank'].mean()

1.3.8 the Geo / Deprivation datasets are stil out of line for 3 entries so do a LEFT join and default the null values to the mean value as a short term solution to fully visualise the maps.

In [17]:
# code to populate the nulls in PopDepMap where there is no deprivation data (Scotland, Wales & some mismatched areas) 
# default to the mean value

# Set missing values to a default of 10 (least deprived)
Ranklist=['IMDRank', 'IncRank',
       'EmpRank', 'EduRank','HealthRank', 'CrimeRank',  'HouseRank',   'EnvRank']

Declist=['IMDDec',    'IncDec', 'EmpDec', 'EduDec',  'HealthDec', 'CrimeDec',  'HouseDec',
       'EnvRank', 'EnvDec']
for colname in Ranklist:
    PopDepMap.loc[PopDepMap[colname].isnull(),colname] = PopDepMap[colname].mean()
for colname in Declist:
    PopDepMap.loc[PopDepMap[colname].isnull(),colname] = PopDepMap[colname].mean()

PopDepMap.IMDRank.mean()  
PopDepMap.IMDDec.mean() 
PopDepMap.loc[PopDepMap['IMDDec'].isnull()].head() # no more nulls

2 Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Do some exploratory data analysis to provide overall context and look for trends and anomalies. Use deciles here to give a concise 1-10 view of Deprivation.

2.1 Deprivation by Region¶

The bar chart shows the Regions in order of mean deprivation and box plots show the differences in the median and spread of the Index of Multiple Deprivation Rank for each Region. The boxplots showed that the ordering by median is different to that by Mean so we add a barchart ordering by Median.

Note that Mean and Median show different results because of the the difference in range and distribution of Deprivation.

These analyses show that the North East and North West of England are the most deprived areas (based on the calculated mean AND the median and lower quartiles shown in the boxplots).

The least deprived area is the South East of England; with a relatively narrow range of deprivation within the quartiles. There is wide variation within regions, all have areas that are classed as the most deprived (decile=1) and the least (decile=10).

    tooltip=['properties.LADname:N',alt.Tooltip(alt.repeat("column"), type="quantitative")]
).properties(

Out[30]:


















    




























The maps above show that these deprivation types show very different spatial distribution to the others and between themselves.

Crime is more specifically clustered in the inner cities.

Housing Deprivation is almost a mirror image of the overall deprivation picture, ie. worst across the South of England and least in the North - no doubt a factor of higher housing costs in the areas that are overall less deprived.

Environmental deprivation is specific to inner cities and some less populated areas - this is likely an effect of the factors making up Environmental deprivation - distance to facilities for less populated areas and pollution for inner cities.

#function to show multi scatter plots for any array and set of attributes
def MultiScatter(array,main,columns,cols,rows):
    fig,axes = plt.subplots(rows,cols,figsize=(20,10),constrained_layout=True) #,constrained_layout=True# figsize=(10, 10)create Figure fig with subplots axes[0,0] to [1,2]

    row=0;col=0
    for i in range(columns): #len(student.columns)
        if temp.columns[i] != main:
            axes[row,col].set(xlabel=temp.columns[i],ylabel=main)
            axes[row,col].scatter(temp[temp.columns[i]],temp[main],alpha=0.4,c='blue')
            col=col+1
        if col >= cols:
            col=0
            row=row+1 
            if row >= rows:
                exit
    plt.show()
    # add this for different colours:   colors=array['RegionName'], c=colors set colours to regions

# create a heatmap showing the correlation values between pairs of attributes

base = alt.Chart(corr_matrix).encode(
    x=alt.X('var1:N',scale=alt.Scale(paddingInner=0),sort=alt.EncodingSortField('index', order='ascending')),
    y=alt.Y('var2:N',scale=alt.Scale(paddingInner=0),sort=alt.EncodingSortField('index', order='ascending')),
)

heatmap = base.mark_rect().encode(
    color=alt.Color('value:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[-1,1],scheme='redblue')),
    tooltip=['value','var1','var2']
    )

text = base.mark_text(baseline='middle').encode(
    alt.Text('value',format='.2f'),
    color=alt.value('white'),
    tooltip=['value','var1','var2']
)

(heatmap + text).properties(width=360,height=360).configure_axis(title=None)

Health is most strongly correlated with Employment and Income.  As we saw earlier, Income and Employment are very highly correlated with each other so we will model Health as a Linear Regression from Employment.













In [42]:



    


# compare the Pearson and Spearman correlations for Health/Employment
# they are almost identical so either could be used

import scipy.stats as stats

column1=PopDepLSOA["HealthRank"];
column2=PopDepLSOA["EmpRank"];

corrPearson, pValPearson = stats.pearsonr(column1,column2)
print ("Pearson's correlation is", corrPearson, "with a p-value of",pValPearson)

corrSpearman, pValSpearman = stats.spearmanr(column1,column2)
print ("Spearman's correlation is", corrSpearman, "with a p-value of",pValSpearman)



    















    






Pearson's correlation is 0.8579618172568885 with a p-value of 0.0
Spearman's correlation is 0.8579618318847234 with a p-value of 0.0



















In [43]:



    


def RegressScatter (pd,colname1,colname2):
# a function to plot a regression line and scatter plot from any 2 columns of a given matrix
    column1=pd[colname1];
    column2=pd[colname2];

    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(column1, column2)

    print ("Slope: ", slope)
    print ("Intercept: ", intercept)
    print ("r_value: ", r_value)
    print ("p_value: ", p_value)
    print ("std_err: ", std_err)
    
    #Calculate 2 points directly from the parameters
    x1=column1.min() 
    x2=column1.max() 
    y1=x1*slope + intercept 
    y2=x2*slope + intercept

    #Plot a scatterplot 
    plt.suptitle(colname1 + ' vs. ' + colname2)
    plt.xlabel(colname1)
    plt.ylabel(colname2)
    plt.scatter(column1,column2 , c = "red", s = 30, alpha = 0.2, linewidth='0')

    #overlay the modelled line 
    plt.plot([x1,x2],[y1,y2])



    















4.2 Health Deprivation Linear Regression¶
Model Health deprivation as a linear regression, predicted by Employment deprivation.

This was originally done with the LSOA rank data but the relationship and the outliers are shown more clearly with the less granular LA district figures and the scatter plots offer more clarity using the deciles instead of ranks.

The results below confirm that Employment provides the best fitted regression, with the highest r-values and lowest p-value.













In [44]:



    


#RegressScatter(PopDepLSOA,'EmpRank','HealthRank')
#RegressScatter(PopDepLAD,'EmpDec','HealthDec')
RegressScatter(PopDepLAD,'EmpDec','HealthDec')



    















    






Slope:  1.261468157966843
Intercept:  -1.4147559249631065
r_value:  0.9347616301040529
p_value:  2.563954937582572e-146
std_err:  0.026760127753821288










    




























This regressions above shows that for every unit decrease in Employment Deprivation ranking, there is a 1.3 decrease in Health Deprivation. P-value is zero (to the accuracy of many decimal places) showing that this relationship is statistically significant.


The scatter plot is also showing that there are some outliers where Health is both more and less deprived than the model would suggest based upon Employment deprivation - these may correspond to the Regions we have identified with Health differences.

Modelling Health as a function of Income deprivation still gives us a reasonable model but with more errors/outliers than that using Employment.















4.3 Health Linear Regression of Regional Subsets¶
Linear regressions are modelled for the region subsets whose Health/Employment correlations most closely resembled each other.


The model for London alone has many outliers - this is possibly a cause of a wider variability in deprivation there.


Linear regression was performed on many subsets of the Regions.  A wide variation in the line slope (from 0.8 for North East to 1.3 for East of England) was observed.  No overall conclusions about the regional subsetting could be drawn without further work.  We conclude that variation within regions is larger than between them.
